{{About|the sporting event held in 1984|the 2015 film|My Little Pony: Equestria Girls – Friendship Games}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}
{{Infobox sporting event organization
|name    = Friendship Games
|image   = Drujba 84.png
|size    = 100px
|caption = Friendship Games logo
|motto   = Sport, Friendship, Peace
|purpose = For athletes who did not participate <br> in the [[1984 Summer Olympics]]
}}

The '''Friendship Games''', or '''Friendship-84''' ({{lang-ru|Дружба-84}}, ''Druzhba-84''), was an international [[multi-sport event]] held between 2 July and 16 September 1984 in the [[Soviet Union]] and eight other [[socialist state]]s which [[1984 Summer Olympics boycott|boycotted]] the [[1984 Summer Olympics]] in [[Los Angeles]].

Although Friendship Games officials denied that the Games were to be a counter-Olympic event<ref name=Eastern-bloc-exceed>{{cite news |date=17 August 1984|title=Eastern-bloc athletes exceed 10 golden efforts |newspaper=[[The Miami News]] |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=3ZImAAAAIBAJ&sjid=bAEGAAAAIBAJ&pg=987,707190}}</ref><ref name=what-might-have-been>{{cite news |date=28 August 1984 |title=Friendship Games show what might have been at LA |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=hpoRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=QOgDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4553,6903778}}</ref> to avoid conflicts with the [[International Olympic Committee]],<ref name=Eastern-bloc-exceed /><ref name=generic-competition>{{cite news|last1=Lowitt |first1=Bruce |date=14 August 1984 |title=Generic competition |newspaper=The [[Times-News (Hendersonville, North Carolina)|Times-News]]| location=[[Hendersonville, North Carolina]] |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=NmwbAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Q04EAAAAIBAJ}}</ref><ref name=peace-dominating /> the competition was often dubbed the [[Eastern Bloc]]'s "alternative Olympics".<ref name=generic-competition /><ref name=Prague-Conference>{{cite news|date=25 May 1984|title=Eastern Bloc calls for alternative Olympics |newspaper=[[Lodi News-Sentinel]] |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=trAzAAAAIBAJ&sjid=QzIHAAAAIBAJ&pg=2707,2998548}}</ref><ref name=Soviet-officials-shy>{{cite news|date=24 August 1984|title=Soviet officials shy from comparing Olympic, Friendship games |newspaper=[[Ottawa Citizen]] |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=jMkyAAAAIBAJ&sjid=XO8FAAAAIBAJ&pg=5432,2027294}}</ref><ref name=Ted-Turner1>{{cite news|date=7 July 1984 |title=Will Turner televise Soviet bloc games?|newspaper=[[The Register-Guard|Eugene Register-Guard]] |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=csUUAAAAIBAJ&sjid=j-EDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5224,1434756}}</ref> Some fifty states took part in the competition. While the boycotting countries were represented by their strongest athletes, other states sent their reserve teams, consisting of athletes who failed to qualify for Los Angeles.<ref name=what-might-have-been />

==Background==
[[File:Juan Antonio Samaranch DF-ST-01-00128.JPEG.jpg|thumb|left| [[Juan Antonio Samaranch]] (''2000 photograph''), [[Presidents of the International Olympic Committee|President of the IOC]], held a conference with the [[Eastern Bloc]] countries in May 1984, attempting to change their decision on boycotting the [[1984 Summer Olympics|Los Angeles Olympics]]. Instead, the socialist states used this meeting to discuss details of their own multi-sport event, the Friendship Games. Samaranch's only success was [[Socialist Republic of Romania|Romania]]'s confirmation that it would not join the boycott.]]

{{See also|1984 Summer Olympics boycott}}

On 8 May 1984, less than three months before the [[1984 Summer Olympics]] were scheduled to begin, the [[Soviet Union]] announced its decision to boycott the Games, citing lack of security for Soviet athletes in [[Los Angeles]].<ref name=Soviet-pullout-rocks-Games>{{cite news |date=9 May 1984 |title=Soviet pullout rocks Games |newspaper=[[The Montreal Gazette]] |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=eVwxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=l6UFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1833,4342317}}</ref> The [[Telegraph Agency of the Soviet Union|TASS]] news agency further accused the [[United States]] of trying to "exploit the Games for its political purposes"<ref name=Alternate-Games-Would-Repudiate-Charter>{{cite news |date=10 May 1984 |title=Alternate Games Would Repudiate Charter |newspaper=[[The Palm Beach Post]] |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=-_EuAAAAIBAJ&sjid=UM8FAAAAIBAJ&pg=1287,7742871}}</ref> stating that the "arrogant, hegemonic course of the Washington administration in international relations is at odds with the noble ideals of the Olympic movement".<ref name=Alternate-Games-Would-Repudiate-Charter />
In an article published by the ''[[London Evening Standard]]'' several hours before the official announcement, [[Victor Louis (journalist)|Victor Louis]] – a Soviet journalist writing for the Western press, thought to be used by the [[Kremlin]] as an unofficial means of leaking information to the West<ref name=Afghanistan-Joins-Boycott>{{cite news |last1=Lowitt |first1=Bruce |date=14 May 1984 |title= Afghanistan Joins Boycott (part 1)|newspaper=The Victoria Advocate |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=-MMcAAAAIBAJ&sjid=p1kEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6804,4042639 }} {{cite news|last1=Lowitt |first1=Bruce |date=14 May 1984 |title= Afghanistan Joins Boycott (part 2)|newspaper=The Victoria Advocate |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=-MMcAAAAIBAJ&sjid=p1kEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5131,4049411}}</ref><ref name=Bulgaria-pulls-out-Reagan-intervenes>{{cite news |date=10 May 1984 |title=Bulgaria pulls out, Reagan intervenes|newspaper=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]] |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=auYNAAAAIBAJ&sjid=G24DAAAAIBAJ&pg=7131,2161071 }}</ref> – first informed the world of the USSR's decision to boycott, adding that detailed plans for the "Soviet bloc's alternative games" had already been made. Louis claimed they would "probably be announced at the last minute to throw the American organization into chaos".<ref name=Bulgaria-pulls-out-Reagan-intervenes /> The article named [[People's Republic of Bulgaria|Bulgaria]] as the possible host country.<ref name=Bulgaria-pulls-out-Reagan-intervenes /> On 10 May, Bulgaria became the first Soviet ally to join the boycott,<ref name=Bulgaria-pulls-out-Reagan-intervenes /> soon followed by [[East Germany]] (also 10 May),<ref name=East-Germany-withdraws-from-Summer-Games>{{cite news |date=10 May 1984 |title=East Germany withdraws from Summer Games|newspaper=The [[Evening Independent]] |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=cAIMAAAAIBAJ&sjid=i1kDAAAAIBAJ&pg=7026,2613126 |location=[[St. Petersburg, Florida]]}}</ref> [[Mongolia]] and [[Vietnam]] (both 11 May).<ref name=Vietnam-Mongolia-join-Games-bailout>{{cite news|date=12 May 1984 |title=Vietnam, Mongolia join Games bailout|newspaper=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]] |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=bOYNAAAAIBAJ&sjid=G24DAAAAIBAJ&pg=7079,2953727}}</ref>

Louis wrote another article on 13 May, for the French ''[[Le Journal du Dimanche]]'',<ref name=Afghanistan-Joins-Boycott /> once again stating that the Soviet Union was contemplating counter-Olympic Games, possibly held in [[Sofia]], the capital of Bulgaria. However, this time he noted that the idea was unlikely, as the Soviets feared that organizing such an event might prompt the [[International Olympic Committee]] to exclude the USSR.<ref name=Afghanistan-Joins-Boycott /> On the same day, Soviet sports commentator Vsevold Kuskuskin, during an interview for [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] television program ''[[This Week (ABC TV series)|This Week with David Brinkley]]'', said the [[Eastern Bloc]] would definitely not organize such games.<ref name=Afghanistan-Joins-Boycott /> Also on 13 May, [[Laos]], [[Czechoslovakia]] and [[Democratic Republic of Afghanistan|Afghanistan]] announced their decision to boycott the Los Angeles games.<ref name=Afghanistan-Joins-Boycott /><ref name=Czechoslovakia-Laos-join-the-list>{{cite news|last1=Joyce |first1=Dick |date=13 May 1984 |title=Czechoslovakia, Laos join the list|newspaper=[[Anchorage Daily News]] |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=-R8fAAAAIBAJ&sjid=facEAAAAIBAJ&pg=1529,6975019 }}</ref>

On 14 May, Marat Gramov, head of the Soviet Olympic Committee, called a press conference to discuss the boycott.<ref name=Soviets-slamming>{{cite news|date=15 May 1984|title=Soviets, slamming Olympics door, charge US plot |newspaper=[[The Christian Science Monitor]] |url=http://www.csmonitor.com/1984/0515/051549.html}}</ref> During the conference, Gramov assured "Moscow would not support any alternative games staged to compete with the Olympics".<ref name=Soviets-slamming /> On the same day, [[People's Republic of Poland|Poland]] stated that, while Eastern Bloc officials had vetoed a counter-Olympics idea, the Bloc would instead "sponsor sports events in various nations as a substitute for participation in the Los Angeles games",<ref name=Soviets-slamming /> holding them at a different time than the Olympics.<ref name=Soviets-slamming />

[[People's Republic of Hungary|Hungary]] became the ninth country to boycott the 1984 Summer Olympics on 16 May, followed by Poland a day later.<ref name=Hungary-joins>{{cite news |date=16 May 1984 |title=Hungary joins Soviet boycott |newspaper=[[Lodi News-Sentinel]] |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=sbAzAAAAIBAJ&sjid=QzIHAAAAIBAJ&pg=5389,2026175}}</ref><ref name=Poland-10th>{{cite news|last1=Barnard |first1=William R. |date=17 May 1984 |title=Poland 10th to join Olympic boycott |newspaper=[[The Deseret News]] |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=4g8fAAAAIBAJ&sjid=D4MDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6350,599674}}</ref>

On 20 May, Olaf Brockmann of Austrian newspaper ''[[Die Presse]]'', citing Alexander Ushakov, head trainer of the Soviet decathlon team, said Eastern Bloc countries were hastily arranging a series of sports events.<ref name=Soviet-Bloc-Discussing>{{cite news |date=20 May 1984 |title=Soviet Bloc Discussing Own Games |newspaper=[[Ocala Star-Banner]] |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=HR8VAAAAIBAJ&sjid=RAYEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6793,2319906}}</ref> Brockmann named five competitions: two track and field athletics meets, one to be held in [[Prague]], Czechoslovakia, and the other in [[East Berlin]] and [[Potsdam]], East Germany; plus fencing, modern pentathlon and boxing events to be held in Poland.<ref name=Soviet-Bloc-Discussing /> Ushakov reportedly said the events would be held either before or after the Olympics, to avoid conflicts with the IOC, which would ban any form of counter-Olympic Games.<ref name=Soviet-Bloc-Discussing />

[[Juan Antonio Samaranch]], [[Presidents of the International Olympic Committee|President of the IOC]], held a conference with Olympic Committees of eleven Eastern Bloc countries (eight of the boycotting states – Bulgaria, Czechoslovakia, East Germany, Hungary, Mongolia, Poland, the Soviet Union and Vietnam – plus [[Cuba]], [[North Korea]] and [[Socialist Republic of Romania|Romania]])<ref name=Communist-nations-plan>{{cite news |date=25 May 1984 |title=Communist nations plan own games |newspaper=Mohave Daily Miner |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=SZUNAAAAIBAJ&sjid=s1YDAAAAIBAJ&pg=1054,3766667 }}</ref> in Prague, Czechoslovakia, starting on 21 May.<ref name=Communist-leaders>{{cite news |date=21 May 1984 |title=Communist leaders confer on Olympics |newspaper=[[The Tuscaloosa News]] |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=XzAjAAAAIBAJ&sjid=66UEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5073,6946151}}</ref> Samaranch hoped to convince the boycotting states to change their position,<ref name=Communist-leaders /> but while Romania assured him it would attend the Los Angeles Olympics,<ref name=Prague-Conference /><ref name=Communist-nations-plan /> the remaining ten countries did not change their stance and even used the meeting to discuss "their own summer games".<ref name=Prague-Conference /><ref name=Communist-nations-plan /> The official announcement was made by Antonin Himl, President of the Czech National Olympic Committee, who appeared on Prague television on 24 May.<ref name=Prague-Conference /><ref name=Communist-nations-plan /> Himl said that, after the Olympic Games ended, various Eastern bloc countries would hold their own sport events in Olympic disciplines.<ref name=Communist-nations-plan /> Himl stated that the games' intention would be to "give athletes who have conscientiously prepared for the past four years a possibility to sell their abilities".<ref name=Communist-nations-plan /> Thus, the Friendship Games idea was officially proclaimed.

Himl said the games would be held after 12 August (i.e. after the Summer Olympics), and that his country, Czechoslovakia, would host gymnastics, archery, women's handball, and women's track and field athletics.<ref name=Boycott-nations>{{cite news |date=25 May 1984 |title= Boycott nations will stage own games |newspaper=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]] |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=d-YNAAAAIBAJ&sjid=G24DAAAAIBAJ&pg=3969,6224193}}</ref> He also gave assurances that the events would be open to all athletes, including those from non-boycotting nations.<ref name=Boycott-nations />

Soon after the meeting, Cuba also announced its decision to boycott the 1984 Summer Olympics.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Maxwell |first1=Evan |date=24 May 1984|title=Cuba Joins Olympic Boycott |newspaper=[[The Los Angeles Times]] |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/676722322.html?dids=676722322:676722322&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=May+24%2C+1984&author=&pub=Los+Angeles+Times}}</ref> By the end of June, [[North Korea]], [[South Yemen]], [[Ethiopia]] and [[Angola]] had done the same.<ref>{{cite news |date=27 May 1984|title=Marxist South Yemen Becomes 12th Country to Drop Out of L.A. Games |newspaper=[[The Los Angeles Times]] |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/676757362.html?dids=676757362:676757362&FMT=CITE&FMTS=CITE:AI&type=historic&date=May+27%2C+1984&author=&pub=Los+Angeles+Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=2 June 1984|title=Ethiopia, North Korea join Olympic boycott|newspaper=The [[Times-News (Hendersonville, North Carolina)|Times-News]]| location=[[Hendersonville, North Carolina]] |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=3bsbAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Rk4EAAAAIBAJ&pg=1974,5867950 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Reich |first1= Kenneth |date=27 June 1984|title=Angola Becomes 15th Nation to Join Olympic Boycott |newspaper=[[The Los Angeles Times]] |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/677016312.html?dids=677016312:677016312&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Jun+27%2C+1984&author=&pub=Los+Angeles+Times}}</ref>

In June, the Soviet Union asked [[Ted Turner]] and his [[Turner Broadcasting System]] to televise the events held in Hungary for American audiences.<ref name=Ted-Turner1 /> Turner eventually declined, but assured that his network would give spot coverage to the Games and treat it as any other sporting event.<ref name=Ted-Turner2>{{cite news |date=7 July 1984|title=Sports People; Turner Backs Off |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/07/07/sports/sports-people-turner-backs-off.html}}</ref>

==Participating nations==
[[File:1984 Friendship Games participants.png|thumb|right|Hosting nations shown in blue, other participants in green]]

Initial estimates placed the number of athletes participating in Soviet event venues at approximately 8,000.<ref name=generic-competition /><ref name=Moscow-to-stage /> Later, the number of expected participants was lowered to 2,300, representing 49 countries.<ref name=generic-competition /><ref name=Good-times>{{cite news|date=18 August 1984|title=Good times are in order at the Friendship Games|newspaper=[[The Deseret News]]|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=k5AzAAAAIBAJ&sjid=A4MDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6955,827200}}</ref><ref name="Infosport">{{cite web|title=Infosport ("1984" section)|url=http://www.infosport.ru/memoryPro/DocMemory.asp|accessdate=29 June 2010|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091026171319/http://www.infosport.ru/memoryPro/DocMemory.asp|archivedate=26 October 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> However, not all the expected athletes showed up.<ref name=Games-open-with-challenge /> The exact number of athletes who took part in events held outside of the Soviet Union is unknown.

While Olympic-boycotting countries were represented by their strongest athletes, other states sent their reserve teams, consisting of athletes who failed to qualify for the 1984 Summer Olympics.<ref name=what-might-have-been />

