Events were hosted by nine countries (Bulgaria, Cuba, Czechoslovakia, East Germany, Hungary, North Korea, Mongolia, Poland, and the Soviet Union) between 2 July and 16 September 1984. With the exception of equestrian jumping, no events were held during the Summer Olympics in Los Angeles (held between 28 July and 12 August).

The Games were contested in 22 Olympic disciplines (all except [[association football]] and [[synchronized swimming]]), and in non-Olympic [[table tennis]], [[tennis]], and [[sambo (martial art)|sambo wrestling]]. Additionally, the Friendship Games included non-Olympic women's shooting and rhythmic gymnastic events but not women's road race cycling, which became an Olympic event in 1984.

===Archery===
{{main|Archery at the Friendship Games}}
The Soviet Union won five out of six possible medals.

[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 183-1984-0603-003, Uwe Hohn.jpg|thumb|left|[[Uwe Hohn]] won the gold medal in javelin throw]]

===Athletics===
{{main|Athletics at the Friendship Games}}
In an interview shortly before the events began, the Soviet team's coach [[Igor Ter-Ovanesyan]] said his athletes beat more than ten world records during the preparations for the competition.<ref name=who-is-coming /> While the Soviet athletes set no new records during the Games, they still dominated, winning more than a half of the gold medals. The only new world record was set by East German [[Irina Meszynski]] in women's discus throw, with 73.36 m.

Athletics was the only discipline which saw participation of recent [[1984 Summer Olympics|Olympic]] gold medalists, with American sprinter [[Alice Brown (athlete)|Alice Brown]] taking part in women's 100-metre run, and West German [[Claudia Losch]] competing in shot put. However, neither won medals.<ref name=Westerners-expected>{{cite news|date=16 August 1984|title=Westerners expected at Communist Games|newspaper=[[The Palm Beach Post]] |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=dAYjAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Us0FAAAAIBAJ&pg=5774,4662666}}</ref><ref>Chmielewski (1987), p. 158</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Harvey |first1=Randy |date=25 August 1984|title=Tired Kratochvilova Beats U.S. Olympic Stars in 400|newspaper=[[The Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref>

In an unusual feat, [[Alberto Juantorena]] (Cuba) and [[Ryszard Ostrowski]] (Poland) both crossed the finish line at exactly the same moment in the men's 800-metre run. After the officials were unable to decide who came first – even after examining a [[photograph]] – both were declared winners.<ref name=peace-dominating />

The annual [[Moscow International Peace Marathon|Moscow marathon]] was declared to be a Friendship Games event in 1984. This caused a minor controversy, as the [[United States Marine Corps|United States Marine]] guards of the [[Embassy of the United States in Moscow|American embassy]], who usually took part in it, withdrew after learning it would be treated as a Friendship Games competition.<ref name=peace-dominating />

===Basketball===
{{main|Basketball at the Friendship Games}}
The Soviet Union won the men's final against Czechoslovakia 105:70, and Cuba came in third ahead of Poland. The USSR also finished first in the women's event, but since it was a [[round-robin tournament]], there were no semifinals or finals.

===Boxing===
{{main|Boxing at the Friendship Games}}
The host nation, Cuba, fully dominated the event, winning eleven out of twelve gold medals. East German [[Torsten Schmitz]] in the [[welterweight]] category was the only non-Cuban to win gold. [[Teófilo Stevenson]], three-time consecutive Olympic gold medalist who lost the chance to win his fourth gold when Cuba boycotted the Los Angeles Games, won the super heavyweight category.

Boxing was one of just three disciplines in which the Soviet Union did not win a gold medal, the others being modern pentathlon and table tennis.

===Canoeing===
{{main|Canoeing at the Friendship Games}}
Hosts East Germany and the Soviet Union won all twelve gold medals, six apiece.

===Cycling===
{{main|Cycling at the Friendship Games}}
The [[Schleizer Dreieck]] in [[Schleiz]], East Germany, usually used as a car or motorcycle race track, served as cycling venue for the individual road race. The event saw participation of top cyclists of the era, including numerous [[Peace Race]] veterans such as [[Uwe Ampler]] and [[Uwe Raab]].

===Diving===
{{main|Diving at the Friendship Games}}
Diving was yet another event dominated by East Germans and Soviets. Gold medalists included [[Aleksandr Portnov]] and [[Brita Baldus]].

===Equestrian===
{{main|Equestrian at the Friendship Games}}
Equestrian events were the only discipline contested at the same time as the 1984 Summer Olympics, as jumping events took place between 6 and 10 August. It was also the only discipline in which West German and Italian athletes won medals.

In individual dressage, [[Yuri Kovshov]] won both gold and silver, riding two different horses.

===Fencing===
{{main|Fencing at the Friendship Games}}
Soviet fencers won most of the men's events, while Hungary won both women's events, thanks to [[Gertrúd Stefanek]] and [[Edit Kovács]].

===Field hockey===
{{main|Field hockey at the Friendship Games}}
The Soviet Union "A" team won the men's tournament, and while the Soviet Union "B" team came in third, fourth-place finishers [[Zimbabwe]] were awarded the bronze medal.

A team representing the [[Democratic Republic of Afghanistan]] also competed in the men's event, but lost all its matches, including a 0:27 loss to East Germany.

===Gymnastics===
{{main|Gymnastics at the Friendship Games}}
In artistic gymnastics, [[Olga Mostepanova]] achieved perfect "10" scores ten times: four in individual competitions, and six in team events.<ref>Chmielewski (1987), p. 169</ref> All fifteen medals in rhythmic gymnastics were won by just four athletes: Bulgarians [[Anelia Ralenkova]] and [[Diliana Gueorguieva]], and Soviets [[Galina Beloglazova]] and [[Dalia Kutkaitė]].

===Handball===
{{main|Handball at the Friendship Games}}
East Germany won the men's event, thanks to an 18:17 win over the Soviet Union, while Poland came in third. [[Péter Kovács (handballer)|Péter Kovács]] of Hungary was the top scorer with 26 goals. The USSR finished first in the women's tournament.

===Judo===
{{main|Judo at the Friendship Games}}
The Soviet Union again won most of the gold medals. The event was also particularly successful for Poland, which won seven medals.

===Modern pentathlon===
{{main|Modern pentathlon at the Friendship Games}}
Hungarian [[László Fábián (pentathlete)|László Fábián]] won the individual competition, and Hungary also won the team event.

===Rowing===
{{main|Rowing at the Friendship Games}}
The USSR took 11 out of 14 gold medals, while East Germany captured the remaining three.

===Sailing===
{{main|Sailing at the Friendship Games}}
Sailing took place on the [[Baltic Sea]], near [[Tallinn]], [[Estonian Soviet Socialist Republic|Estonian SSR]] (where the [[sailing at the 1980 Summer Olympics]] also took place), with the exception of 470 and Finn classes, which were contested on [[Lake Balaton]] in Hungary. Soviets and East Germans won all of the gold medals. [[Canada]] and [[Finland]] won their only Friendship Games medals.

===Shooting===
{{main|Shooting at the Friendship Games}}
While most disciplines mimicked the Olympic Games in terms of events, women's shooting included non-Olympic competitions, namely the [[10 metre air pistol]] and [[50 metre rifle three positions]] events.

[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 183-1987-0619-033, Sylvia Gerasch.jpg|thumb|[[Sylvia Gerasch]] ''(1987 photograph)'', a 15-year-old, set the world record in women's 100 m breaststroke]]

===Swimming===
{{main|Swimming at the Friendship Games}}
Five new world records were set during the competition. [[Sergei Zabolotnov]]'s result of 1:58.41 in men's 200 metre backstroke excited the crowd, as it was some one and a half seconds better than [[Rick Carey]]'s result during the Olympics.<ref>Chmielewski (1987), p. 173</ref> Fifteen-year-old [[Sylvia Gerasch]] of [[East Germany]] set the world record in women's 100 m breaststroke and was also part of the relay team that beat the 4 × 100 m medley record.<ref name=Soviet-officials-shy />

===Table tennis===
{{main|Table tennis at the Friendship Games}}
Table tennis, a non-Olympic sport at that time, was the only event hosted by North Korea, which won four out of seven gold medals. Notably, the [[People's Republic of China]], which was at odds with most socialist states following the [[Sino-Soviet split]], took part in the event.

===Tennis===
{{main|Tennis at the Friendship Games}}
Soviet players dominated the singles category, and also won the men's doubles event. The Czechoslovakian women's double team was the only non-Soviet team to win gold.

===Volleyball===
{{main|Volleyball at the Friendship Games}}
Not surprisingly, the Soviet team finished first in the men's event, over Cuba and Poland. In women's tournament, Cuba won the final against the USSR.

===Water polo===
{{main|Water polo at the Friendship Games}}
The Soviet team – composed mostly of the players who won gold during the 1980 Summer Olympics – finished first, while Hungary and Cuba took the second and third spots.

===Weightlifting===
{{main|Weightlifting at the Friendship Games}}
Dominated by Bulgaria and the Soviet Union, the event saw thirty world records broken,<ref name=Chmielewski-p186>Chmielewski (1987), p. 186</ref> including two in the super heavyweight category, set by [[Anatoly Pisarenko]].

===Wrestling===
{{main|Wrestling at the Friendship Games}}
In addition to [[freestyle wrestling|freestyle]] and [[Greco-Roman wrestling|Greco-Roman]] events, non-Olympic [[sambo (martial art)|sambo]] wrestling events were also contested. Sambo was the only event hosted by Mongolia.

